ale development investments working to transform villagers into Indigenous entrepreneurs ready to capitalize on Peru's new national brand and access the constantly deferred promise of national growth. That meant identifying as Indigenous, where few actively did so; identifying as an entrepreneur, in a place where single-minded devotion to a business went against the tendency to diversify income sources; and identifying every dimension of one's daily life as a resource, despite the unwelcome intimacy this required. Theorizing growth as an affective project that requires constant physical and emotional labor, Acts of Growth follows a diverse group of Andean residents through the exhausting work of making an economy grow.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszPeruzCaylloma (Province) 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszPeruzCaylloma (Province). 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszPeruzEspinar (Province) 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszPeruzEspinar (Province). 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruzCaylloma (Province)xEconomic conditions. 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruzEspinar (Province)xEconomic conditions. 0aRural developmentzPeruzCaylloma (Province) 0aRural developmentzPeruzCaylloma (Province). 0aRural developmentzPeruzEspinar (Province) 0aRural developmentzPeruzEspinar (Province). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh  aAndes.  aPeru.  aabundance.  aaffect.  adevelopment.  aentrepreneurship.  aextraction.  agrowth.  aindigeneity.  aneoliberalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363095640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503630956423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co